title: [XLA:TPU] Fixes a bug in synchronous memory call ops conversion to async in memory space assignment. The bug showed up when the consumer of a replaced sync instruction is consumed multiple times by the same instruction.
body:
[XLA:TPU] Fixes a bug in synchronous memory call ops conversion to async in memory space assignment. The bug showed up when the consumer of a replaced sync instruction is consumed multiple times by the same instruction.

The issue was that the algorithm was not using the correct allocation sequence when dealing with such repeated consumer instructions.

This CL fixes the bug by using the correct allocation sequence.

title: PR #18595: Verify device compatibility for execution early
body:
PR #18595: Verify device compatibility for execution early

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/openxla/xla/pull/18595

Let us verify that all the devices to run a PJRT executable are compatible with the device that was used to build the executable. Currently we only verify the compatibility on each device separately, just before running the executable on the device.

This fixes a problem where running an executable with a collective on two different devices crashes on NCCL timeout. When only one of the device will not pass the compatibility check while the other device (the one passes the check) runs, the running device will hang on the NCCL collective (since the incompatible device program has not been executed).

title: PR #18765: Add support for fusion operations in while loop analysis.
body:
PR #18765: Add support for fusion operations in while loop analysis.

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/openxla/xla/pull/18765

In late optimizations, while loop analysis was unable to handle the fused operations, primarily for `GetLoopInductionVariableIndex` and `ComputeWhileLoopTripCount`. This patch handles that. 

Summary of the changes:

  * Enhanced `GetGTEOperandIndex` to `GetUniqueGTEDependenceIndex`
  * When brute-forcing the trip count, we want to evaluate the operations recursively instead of just evaluating the operation at hand.

Note: This PR also has the HloEvaluator changes from #18563 as they are required for this to work. After that PR gets merged, I will rebase this for a clean merge.
Copybara import of the project:

--

title: [XLA] Optimize layout_assignment.
body:
[XLA] Optimize layout_assignment.

* Use an `absl::flat_hash_map<..., std::unique_ptr<OperandLayoutConstraint>` instead of a std::map<> for operand_constraints_ in LayoutConstraints. We aren't using the ordering property of std::map<> and only need pointer stability of values, so the absl container is faster.
* Avoid multiple map lookups. We were doing an update-or-insert pattern with three map lookups, but we can do it with one if we change the API of LayoutConstraints to return a reference to the `std::unique_ptr<OperandLayoutConstraint>.`
author: copybara-service[bot]

title: [XLA] Small optimizations to LayoutAssignment::Init().
body:
[XLA] Small optimizations to LayoutAssignment::Init().

* I can see no reason why we're troversing every instruction just to find instructions in added_copies_, when we have a pointer right there in that set. (The only reason I can think of is that these instructions might no longer exist, but as far as I can tell that isn't the case.) Traverse over added_copies_ during copy removal, rather than every instruction in the module.
* Remove call to CallGraph::Build(). The only caller of this function is LayoutAssignment::Run(), and it unconditionally rebuilds the call graph immediately after the call to LayoutAssignment::Init().
author: copybara-service[bot]

Avoid computing the instruction postorder twice in LayoutAssignment::Run() for a transformation that does not need to be done in topological order. Also fuse two loops that iterate over all instructions for better locality.

title: Introduce base class GraphConditional

Introduce base class GraphConditional

A `GraphConditional` represents a conditional in a command buffer and is an opaque handle that can be passed to set-condition kernels. (A set-condition kernel sets the value of the conditional based on whether the associated nested commmand buffer should be executed or not.)

title: Make TritonSupportTest surface sanitizer issues
body:
Make TritonSupportTest surface sanitizer issues

TritonSupportTest relies on a death test for some of its assertion because Triton doesn't allow graceful error handling for some of the cases we want to test.

This death test also used to succeed when the code under test triggered a santizer violation.

So this change makes it fail on those sanitizer violations and will be surface those in the log.

Ideally we would tightly control in which code path each death test terminates, but unfortunately most of them don't have indicative error message. Some just call `std::abort` without an error message. Some just die in accessing an empty `std::optional`, etc. So the best we can do is make sure that we detect sanitizer errors and report these as test failures.

body:
Bumps [werkzeug](https://github.com/pallets/werkzeug) from 3.0.3 to 3.0.6.
Release notes

Sourced from werkzeug's releases.

3.0.6

This is the Werkzeug 3.0.6 security fix release, which fixes security issues but does not otherwise change behavior and should not result in breaking changes.

PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/Werkzeug/3.0.6/ Changes: https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/changes/#version-3-0-6

  • Fix how max_form_memory_size is applied when parsing large non-file fields. GHSA-q34m-jh98-gwm2
  • safe_join catches certain paths on Windows that were not caught by ntpath.isabs on Python < 3.11. GHSA-f9vj-2wh5-fj8j

3.0.5

This is the Werkzeug 3.0.5 fix release, which fixes bugs but does not otherwise change behavior and should not result in breaking changes.

PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/Werkzeug/3.0.5/ Changes: https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/changes/#version-3-0-5 Milestone: https://github.com/pallets/werkzeug/milestone/37?closed=1

  • The Watchdog reloader ignores file closed no write events. #2945
  • Logging works with client addresses containing an IPv6 scope. #2952
  • Ignore invalid authorization parameters. #2955
  • Improve type annotation fore SharedDataMiddleware. #2958
  • Compatibility with Python 3.13 when generating debugger pin and the current UID does not have an associated name. #2957

3.0.4

This is the Werkzeug 3.0.4 fix release, which fixes bugs but does not otherwise change behavior and should not result in breaking changes.

title: [XLA:GPU] Only cache fusible instructions in FusionDeduplicationCache.
body:
[XLA:GPU] Only cache fusible instructions in FusionDeduplicationCache.

This is an optimization of compile time. `deduplicated_id_map` in `FusionDeduplicationCache::Create` uses `HloInstruction::Identical` to compare instructions that have identical hash. There are not that many comparisons need to happen and they're usually very fast, but there is a one particular patter that causes problems:

```
some_tuple = (f32[10], f32[10], ...) tuple(...)
gte0 = get-tuple-element(some_tuple), index=0
gte1 = get-tuple-element(some_tuple), index=1
```

`gte0` and `gte1` have the same hash, so they need to be compared with `HloInstruction::Identical`. Due to the generic implementation of `Identical`, operands will be compared first. It can happen that the tuple `some_tuple` has thousand of element. In that case `Shape::Equal` takes a lot of time.

Since `get-tuple-element` can't be part of a fusion itself, there is no point to get cache entries for instructions that are not fusible.

title: PR #18766: [NVIDIA] Fix the segfault in scatter_determinism_expander when running Transformer Engine
body:
PR #18766: [NVIDIA] Fix the segfault in scatter_determinism_expander when running Transformer Engine

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/openxla/xla/pull/18766

## Issue:
When running TE using XLA with xla_gpu_determinisitc_ops=true, the prefix scan inside the scatter determinism expander caused segfault when then there is only one update in the scatter operation. 
### Steps to reproduce:
```
docker run -it --rm --ipc=host --gpus=all ghcr.io/nvidia/jax:pax-2024-10-18
cd /opt/transformer-engine
pip install -r ./examples/jax/encoder/requirements.txt
XLA_FLAGS="${XLA_FLAGS} --xla_gpu_deterministic_ops" pytest examples/jax/encoder/test_single_gpu_encoder.py
```

The scatter determinism expander assumed the original scatter operation is not deterministic, meaning the case where there is only one index-update pair is not possible. However, if the creator of the scatter operation did not mark the scatter operation to have unique_indices, the scatter determinism expander pass will still match and be applied. In this case, the prefix scan implementation will have a segfault because the log2ceiling of num_indices=1 is 0, leading to direct return in the prefix scan without getting into the loop body, and hence a nullptr update will be returned.

## Changes:
1. Modified the implementation of pattern matching of scatter_determinism_expander, so that even if the unique_indices flag of the scatter operation is not set properly, we will still check the number of indices to make sure the pass is not applied on the scatter with one index.
2. Modified the implementation of prefix scan so that even if the loop body is not entered, the correct update will be returned.
3. Added checks before final CreateScatter operation to explicitly check if any args of the new scatter operation is nullptr. After this, even if any args is nullptr, the pass will fail explicitly instead of having a segfault.
4. Added a test for the case where there is only one index-update pair, and make sure the scatter_determinism_expander pass does not match in this case.
Copybara import of the project:

--

The scatter determinism expander assumed the original scatter operation
is not deterministic, meaning the case where there is only one
index-update pair is not possible. However, if the creator of the
scatter operation did not mark the scatter operation to have
unique_indices, the scatter determinism expander pass will still match
and be applied. In this case, the prefix scan implementation will have
a segfault because the log2ceiling of num_indices=1 is 0, leading to
direct return in the prefix scan without getting into the loop body, and
hence a nullptr update will be returned.

Changes:
1. Modified the implementation of pattern matching of
scatter_determinism_expander, so that even if the unique_indices flag of
the scatter operation is not set properly, we will still check the
number of indices to make sure the pass is not applied on the scatter
with one index.
2. Modified the implementation of prefix scan so that even if the loop
body is not entered, the correct update will be returned.
3. Added checks before final CreateScatter operation to explicitly
check if any args of the new scatter operation is nullptr. After this,
even if any args is nullptr, the pass will fail explicitly instead of

4. Added a test for the case where there is only one index-update pair,
and make sure the scatter_determinism_expander pass does not match in

title: PR #18326: [NVIDIA] Complete the optimization of deterministic scatter operations
body:
PR #18326: [NVIDIA] Complete the optimization of deterministic scatter operations

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/openxla/xla/pull/18326

This PR is the 2nd step (out of 2) to improve the performance of deterministic scatter. Originally, the scatter op will be expanded to be deterministic in xla/service/ScatterExpander.cc. However, since it took a while-loop-based approach, the performance is extremely poor. We designed and implemented a prefix-scan-based approach to rewrite the scatter operation to be an efficient deterministic scatter. This PR completes the optimization of deterministic scatter operations with non-scalar indices and updates.

The change of this PR is on top of https://github.com/openxla/xla/pull/17886

Design doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1K204VZR3OP0SUDOPsGUYgIIDf2ucTKEC4yQj8XRG2SA/edit

Bugs resolved: https://github.com/jax-ml/jax/issues/17844
Copybara import of the project:

Support scatter with non-scalar indices and updates

[XLA] Speed up the HLO DCE pass.

As in HloModule::RemoveUnusedComputations, we can simply perform a DFS over the computations both to find used computations and to trigger RunOnComputation on any used computations. We then remove all unreachable computations.

This improves over the existing code because we avoid repeatedly calling HloModule::MakeComputationPostOrder(), each call to which requires traversing every instruction in every computation. Instead, we can perform a single traversal of the computations.

title: [GpuCommandBuffer] Move creation of ScopedGpuGraphExec into subclasses
body:
[GpuCommandBuffer] Move creation of ScopedGpuGraphExec into subclasses

The `ScopedGpuGraphExec` type is an RAII wrapper that changes the executable graph handle of a nested command buffer to a given value and restores it to its old value during destruction.

It's needed to handle updates of an existing executable graph. Since nested command buffers don't have their own executable graph this wrapper helps with making the executable graph of the root command buffer available to its nested command buffers.

This change makes all of this happen in platform specific sublasses by providing an pure virtual function declaration `ActivateScopedGpuGraphExec` which returns a unique pointer to a base class of the RAII wrapper.
author: copybara-service[bot]

title: [GpuCommandBuffer] Move GpuGraphHandle and GpuGraphExecHandle to subclasses
body:
[GpuCommandBuffer] Move GpuGraphHandle and GpuGraphExecHandle to subclasses

The two members `GpuGraphHandle graph_` and `GpuGraphExecHandle exec_` are getting moved into the platform specific subclasses. This is now possible since all the code that was using these members was migrated previously.

`GpuDriver` methods that previously have been called from the `GpuCommandBuffer` destructor also also getting inlined into the destructors of the subclasses.

title: Use synchronized initialization feature (as opposed to connect, then sync).
body:
Use synchronized initialization feature (as opposed to connect, then sync).

---

Consider this error pattern (before this CL):
1) 4 slice McJax workload is scheduled on Cloud GKE.
2) Slice 0, 1, 2's TPU hosts invoke `jax.distributed.initialize()`.
3) Everyone is still waiting for slice 3.
4) Slice 1 crashes due to a transient GKE error (e.g. maintenance event).
5) Because slice 1 goes away unexpectedly, slice 0's service panics. The service is stopped. **Slice 0 and slice 2 goes down** because of the service crash.

---

**The restarts in the last step are unnecessary, and cause additional scheduling overhead.** With the synchronized initialization feature, we allow TPU hosts to restart and join again silently WITHOUT causing the entire cluster to crash. At this point, no meaningful Jax program has run yet, so silent restarts are harmless.

Restarts should only cause the entire cluster to crash AFTER init, where cluster restart is the only way to recover from a possibly inconsistent state.

---

This has a few benefits:
* Simplify state changes during init to be all-or-nothing op: Nobody will send heartbeat until everybody in the cluster has acked. That's less error flows to reason about during init.

* This helps with consistent in-sync restarts. There's no weird staggering / cascading restart flows regardless of what the scheduler does.

* Move business logic into coord service (pjrt/distributed as simple wrapper).
author: copybara-service[bot]
